<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="116" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,150,573]" pageId="1" pageNumber="116">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,274,150,176]" pageId="1" pageNumber="116">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Small species. Frons trapezoid, with median furrow, with 2–4 supra-antennal setae, and 4–4–4 frontal setae. Flagellomere 1 bean-shaped or rounded; arista sub-apical. Anepisternum bare. Scutellum with 4 setae, anterior shorter. Fore tibia without isolated setae, fore tarsomere 5 longer than tarsomere 4, tapered in distal half. Mid tibia without isolated setae, with a dorsal setal palisade, which is usually not complete. Hind tibia with dorsal setal palisade and posterodorsal setulae. Wing with C short; R 
<subScript attach="left" box="[800,825,313,327]" fontSize="6" pageId="1" pageNumber="116">2+3</subScript>
present, vestigial or absent; Rs with a small angulate thickening near apex. Abdomen of female with a sclerotized ovipositor of varied structure. Male terminalia small; anal tube long.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,1035,402,428]" pageId="1" pageNumber="116" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,150,573]" box="[199,1035,402,428]" pageId="1" pageNumber="116">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,353,402,428]" pageId="1" pageNumber="116">Distribution.</emphasis>
Palaearctic, Nearctic, Neotropical and Afrotropical Regions.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="116" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,150,573]" pageId="1" pageNumber="116">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,438,464]" pageId="1" pageNumber="116">Remarks.</emphasis>
This genus is similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Coquillett" authorityName="Coquillett. Disney" authorityYear="2006" box="[603,871,438,464]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Pseudacteon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="116" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[603,746,438,464]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="116">Pseudacteon</emphasis>
Coquillett
</taxonomicName>
, differing largely by the pointed apical foretarsomere. The phylogeny of the genus is unclear. 
<bibRefCitation author="Brown, B. V." box="[666,824,474,501]" pageId="1" pageNumber="116" pagination="1 - 144" refId="ref2619" refString="Brown, B. V. (1992) Generic revision of Phoridae of the Nearctic Region and phylogenetic classification of Phoridae, Sciadoceridae and Ironomyiidae (Diptera: Phoridea). Memoirs of the Entomological Society of Canada, 164, 1 - 144. https: // doi. org / 10.4039 / entm 124164 fv" type="journal article" year="1992">Brown (1992)</bibRefCitation>
proposed that the genus was adelphotaxa of 
<taxonomicName authority="Coquillett. Disney (2006 b)" authorityName="Coquillett. Disney" authorityYear="2006" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Pseudacteon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="116" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="116">Pseudacteon</emphasis>
Coquillett. 
<bibRefCitation author="Disney, R. H. L." box="[330,505,510,536]" pageId="1" pageNumber="116" pagination="473 - 521" refId="ref3015" refString="Disney, R. H. L. (2006 b) Scuttle flies (Diptera: Phoridae). Part I. all genera except Megaselia. Fauna of Arabia, 22, 473 - 521." type="journal article" year="2006">Disney (2006b)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
and Disney et. al. (2010) suggested that it belongs to the tribe 
<taxonomicName box="[1194,1362,510,536]" pageId="1" pageNumber="116" rank="tribe" tribe="Gymnophorini">Gymnophorini</taxonomicName>
, based on the character of the vestige of a dorsal abdominal gland.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
